00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:04.771
ALEX KOMOROSKE: OK.

00:09:04.771 --> 00:09:05.960
So 12 to 20 for apps.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:08.860
Maybe double that,
like 40 or so.

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:12.117
ELISABETH MORANT: Over
100 websites a month.

00:09:12.117 --> 00:09:12.950
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Wow.

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:14.040
That's actually
really impressive.

00:09:14.040 --> 00:09:15.090
I didn't realize it was
going to be that big.

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:15.430
ELISABETH MORANT: See?

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:16.930
That right there
is reach in action.

00:09:16.930 --> 00:09:18.850
It's so easy for people
to just tap a link

00:09:18.850 --> 00:09:23.090
and visit tons of new
sites with no friction.

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:26.070
And in fact, it turns out
that 85% of US retailers'

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:28.110
mobile traffic is on the
web, and that accounts

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:29.307
for 90% of their revenue.

00:09:29.307 --> 00:09:30.140
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Wow.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:32.264
ELISABETH MORANT: And now
this is just one example,

00:09:32.264 --> 00:09:35.880
and this is why I consider
reach the superpower of the web.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.960
So the way I think of it is--
bear with me-- you want people

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:42.410
to form a meaningful
relationship with your stuff,

00:09:42.410 --> 00:09:44.570
but first people
have to find it.

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:48.100
So it's kind of like the web
is one big speed dating venue

00:09:48.100 --> 00:09:50.890
where you can jump from person
to person and get to know them

00:09:50.890 --> 00:09:53.420
a little bit, just like you can
jump from website to website

00:09:53.420 --> 00:09:55.461
and get to know it a little
bit before committing

00:09:55.461 --> 00:09:58.310
and developing a relationship
with that content.

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:00.730
And you're never afraid
to necessarily click

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:02.860
a link because what's the
worst that can happen?

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:04.610
After five minutes,
the bell rings and you

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:06.406
move onto the next place.

00:10:06.406 --> 00:10:09.030
And the point is that then, when
you decide you want to commit,

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:11.450
you can build that
relationship over time.

00:10:11.450 --> 00:10:13.490
And so we take reach for
granted but it's really

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:14.962
as important as ever.

00:10:14.962 --> 00:10:16.920
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So that's
reach, but of course,

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:19.660
just as important on
mobile is performance.

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:21.160
But what does good
performance mean?

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:23.710
How do you know when you're done
and when you're good enough?

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:25.210
ELISABETH MORANT:
Well, that's easy.

00:10:25.210 --> 00:10:27.030
It's just the amount of time
it takes a page to load.

00:10:27.030 --> 00:10:28.010
ALEX KOMOROSKE:
So page load time

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:30.301
is something that we've all
known about as a community.

00:10:30.301 --> 00:10:31.680
We call it PLT or whatever.

00:10:31.680 --> 00:10:34.100
We have good understanding,
got good tools.

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:36.047
There's whole conferences on it.

00:10:36.047 --> 00:10:37.880
That's not to say we're
perfect, by the way.

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:39.588
There's a lot of us
who don't necessarily

00:10:39.588 --> 00:10:41.240
practice what we preach here.

00:10:41.240 --> 00:10:43.990
But on mobile, other
metrics matter, too,

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:45.115
like scrolling performance.

00:10:45.115 --> 00:10:47.700
To have the illusion that
the content is sticking

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:49.310
to your finger as
you scroll, you've

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:51.660
got to hit 60 frames
per second consistently.

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:53.160
But which of these
metrics should we

00:10:53.160 --> 00:10:56.020
look at and which one
should we be optimizing?

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:58.472
So the answer to that is this
concept that we call RAIL.

00:10:58.472 --> 00:11:00.180
ELISABETH MORANT:
Great, another acronym.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:00.890
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Of course.

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:01.990
What did you expect?

00:11:01.990 --> 00:11:03.810
So it's basically a
conceptual framework

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:06.380
for knowing when you have
good enough performance.

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:09.080
So the key insight is when
is performance good enough?

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:11.162
Well, when the user
can't perceive it.

00:11:11.162 --> 00:11:12.370
That's when it's good enough.

00:11:12.370 --> 00:11:13.770
ELISABETH MORANT: I'm pretty
sure Don Draper didn't actually

00:11:13.770 --> 00:11:14.365
say that.

00:11:14.365 --> 00:11:15.490
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Good catch.

00:11:15.490 --> 00:11:17.031
He didn't say that,
as far as I know,

00:11:17.031 --> 00:11:18.733
but he might have
said it if only

00:11:18.733 --> 00:11:20.490
he had cared about
this kind of stuff.

00:11:20.490 --> 00:11:21.865
But the point is
there's actually

00:11:21.865 --> 00:11:23.280
a lot of research on this.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:26.050
So if you're trying to get
that illusion of smooth motion,

00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:28.300
of course you want to
hit 60 frames per second,

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:32.850
which means 16.67 milliseconds
to put each frame on screen.

00:11:32.850 --> 00:11:34.970
Now, if you want to
have the user feel

00:11:34.970 --> 00:11:37.040
that the thing happened
instantaneously,

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:40.060
research tells us you've
got about 100 milliseconds.

00:11:40.060 --> 00:11:42.930
And if you do something
within one second, well then,

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:45.769
someone's train of
thought can stay on it,

00:11:45.769 --> 00:11:47.310
and if you take more
than 10 seconds,

00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:49.690
well then they're off playing
solitaire or something.

00:11:49.690 --> 00:11:51.080
ELISABETH MORANT: Definitely
took more than 10 seconds.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:53.121
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Thank you
for that great example.

00:11:53.121 --> 00:11:56.690
So anyway, these are the
golden standard for you to hit,

00:11:56.690 --> 00:11:58.320
and RAIL is basically
just hitting

00:11:58.320 --> 00:12:01.890
these goals in the context
of your web performance.

00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:05.150
So the first one is
R for reaction time.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.740
So basically, this
is exactly when

00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:09.880
the user puts their
finger down on the glass

00:12:09.880 --> 00:12:10.890
and starts interacting.

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:13.474
You have 100 milliseconds to do
something, to show you got it.

00:12:13.474 --> 00:12:14.681
ELISABETH MORANT: Yeah, sure.

00:12:14.681 --> 00:12:16.781
Otherwise, the app
feels broken or slow.

00:12:16.781 --> 00:12:17.780
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Exactly.

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:20.560
So that's 100 milliseconds
to change the button color

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:23.120
or to show a loading
indicator or show, I got it.

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:24.620
I'm not frozen.

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:26.660
Next one is Animation time.

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:28.470
You've got, of course,
60 frames per second

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:32.380
is the gold standard, which
means 16.67 milliseconds.

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:35.470
Now, that's not a lot of
time, so if you do anything,

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:39.300
you might miss that, so you
have to really, really careful.

00:12:39.300 --> 00:12:42.049
So the next one is Idle.

00:12:42.049 --> 00:12:43.840
ELISABETH MORANT: Why
is Idle part of RAIL?

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:45.470
ALEX KOMOROSKE:
So you have to do

00:12:45.470 --> 00:12:48.280
some work that's going to take
some time, like image decodes

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:52.060
or whatever, and you can't do
it when the user is interacting,

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:54.046
so a good time is when
the user doesn't have

00:12:54.046 --> 00:12:55.170
their finger on the screen.

00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:56.050
ELISABETH MORANT: Right.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:12:58.591
ALEX KOMOROSKE: However, what
if the user's finger comes back

00:12:58.591 --> 00:13:00.170
in while you're doing that work?

00:13:00.170 --> 00:13:00.650
ELISABETH MORANT: I see.

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:01.920
You don't want to be
the middle of idle time

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:03.570
because otherwise, you're not
going to be able to react.

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:05.300
The user might think
the app is broken.

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:05.520
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Right.

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:07.710
So you want to make sure
you chunk up your work you

00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:09.840
that you even in idle
so if at any point

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:12.400
the user starts interacting
with you, you're good to go

00:13:12.400 --> 00:13:16.170
and can hit that 100
milliseconds, the R of RAIL.

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:19.100
And the last one, of course,
is our friend Load time.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:22.197
Of course, it still matters,
if not more, on mobile.

00:13:22.197 --> 00:13:24.030
And the gold standard
here to keep the train

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:25.782
of thought solid is one second.

00:13:25.782 --> 00:13:27.990
ELISABETH MORANT: I wish
everything loaded that fast.

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:28.865
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Yeah.

00:13:28.865 --> 00:13:29.920
It's pretty low, right?

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:32.530
Remember, this is for
perfect performance,

00:13:32.530 --> 00:13:34.450
and things like Quick
and Service Worker

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:37.590
actually make this feasible
for the first time.

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:40.070
And of course, if you can't
get your entire site loaded up

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:41.910
on screen, well,
the next best thing

00:13:41.910 --> 00:13:45.200
is putting reasonable pixels
on screen to show I've loaded,

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:46.559
I'm working, I'm not just stuck.

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:48.350
ELISABETH MORANT: Sure,
some loading image.

00:13:48.350 --> 00:13:48.890
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Right.

00:13:48.890 --> 00:13:50.270
ELISABETH MORANT: So this
is all great in theory,

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:52.010
but what does it actually
mean in practice?

00:13:52.010 --> 00:13:54.301
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So RAIL is
a great conceptual framework

00:13:54.301 --> 00:13:55.470
for us across the community.

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:57.980
So for browser
vendors in particular,

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:00.080
it means giving
you as developers

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:02.690
more headroom, more
space for your own code

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:06.990
to do this work so that you
don't cross those boundaries.

00:14:06.990 --> 00:14:09.120
So the Chrome Web
Platform team is

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:12.450
way over-- I think 200
engineers last time I checked.

00:14:12.450 --> 00:14:14.100
A lot of people,
the vast majority,

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:16.630
work on some aspect
of performance.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:19.520
We've been doing tons of
work, vast re-architectures,

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:21.570
to optimize for
mobile performance.

00:14:21.570 --> 00:14:24.730
Now, we don't have time to dive
into any of these in any depth,

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:27.170
but let me just pick one.

00:14:27.170 --> 00:14:29.220
So a couple months ago,
we launched this feature

00:14:29.220 --> 00:14:30.470
called the Scheduler.

00:14:30.470 --> 00:14:32.180
And the basic idea
is that when you

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:34.890
start interacting with a
page, that's when, of course,

00:14:34.890 --> 00:14:38.390
you want to prioritize scrolling
and frames over everything

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:39.260
else.

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:42.324
And it turns out that this
can have a really big impact,

00:14:42.324 --> 00:14:43.990
especially during
page load when there's

00:14:43.990 --> 00:14:45.780
lots of work being done.

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:48.740
So here we've got a video,
and if you can roll the video,

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:51.580
we have on the left with
the scheduler, on the right

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:52.390
without.

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:55.300
We refresh the page so
we're doing tons of work,

00:14:55.300 --> 00:14:57.980
and you can see the one
on the left scrolls way

00:14:57.980 --> 00:15:00.740
more smoothly than
the one on the right.

00:15:00.740 --> 00:15:04.140
So this is a great example of
RAIL motivating work for us

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:06.570
as browser vendors to
make your site just

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:07.820
get faster automatically.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:09.276
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:09.276 --> 00:15:09.776
Thanks.

00:15:14.180 --> 00:15:16.640
So if we can move on
to the next slide.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:18.630
So it's not just on us.

00:15:18.630 --> 00:15:21.770
It's also on developers
that work with us.

00:15:21.770 --> 00:15:23.570
And so part of it
is better tooling

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:26.880
so that you can understand your
own performance really well.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.720
So of course, DevTools
is incredibly powerful.

00:15:29.720 --> 00:15:32.250
A new feature that you can try
out in Canary behind the flag

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:35.400
today is a feature
called Filmstrip.

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:38.530
So what it does, it shows
you-- you can see it up there

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:41.310
in that row of
images-- it shows what

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:43.380
pixels were on screen
at different parts

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:44.830
as you loaded the page.

00:15:44.830 --> 00:15:48.430
And so you can see here
this random cwilso guy,

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:51.870
his blog is hitting about
eight seconds for the pixels

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:54.640
to be on screen, which
is way past the one

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:56.410
second that you want with RAIL.

00:15:56.410 --> 00:15:58.460
And so now, of course,
you dig in with DevTools

00:15:58.460 --> 00:15:59.620
and figure out what's going on.

00:15:59.620 --> 00:16:01.619
ELISABETH MORANT: So
DevTools is really powerful

00:16:01.619 --> 00:16:03.930
but you basically need a
PhD to understand all of it.

00:16:03.930 --> 00:16:04.804
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Yeah.

00:16:04.804 --> 00:16:06.870
It's so overwhelmingly
powerful sometimes.

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:08.460
So we're also
working on tools that

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:10.660
will make it so that
you can open up DevTools

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:12.930
and it will say, hey,
you're consistently

00:16:12.930 --> 00:16:14.640
missing the A in RAIL.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:18.520
Turns out that this third party
script, this analytic script,

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:20.740
is doing way too
much work on scroll.

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:22.060
Consider removing it.

00:16:22.060 --> 00:16:24.020
And so making it much
easier for you to dive in

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:26.112
without having to get a PhD.

00:16:26.112 --> 00:16:27.570
And of course, the
last one is just

00:16:27.570 --> 00:16:29.400
holding ourselves
as web developers

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:30.920
to a higher standard.

00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:33.660
So the I/O web app
is an amazing example

00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:37.070
of a highly responsive, 60
frames per second web app.

00:16:37.070 --> 00:16:41.300
Now, it wasn't easy to build but
it is getting easier and easier

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:42.550
every day.

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:44.520
And all of us,
every single time we

00:16:44.520 --> 00:16:46.930
include a third party
script or resource

00:16:46.930 --> 00:16:49.361
or we fetch out to another
third party domain,

00:16:49.361 --> 00:16:51.110
we should ask ourselves,
is this worth it?

00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:55.900
Is this going to make me go
past those goals in RAIL?

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:58.060
So there's only so much
time to cover performance.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:00.190
The point is that we've
made a lot of big strides

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:02.150
and I think this is a
great framework for us

00:17:02.150 --> 00:17:03.960
as a community.

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:06.650
ELISABETH MORANT: So the web
has a superpower of reach,

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:09.270
and now it's possible to have
60 frames per second, even

00:17:09.270 --> 00:17:11.420
for the most
complex mobile apps,

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:13.390
but what the web is
missing is the ability

00:17:13.390 --> 00:17:16.319
for users to build meaningful
relationships with the stuff

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:17.653
that they find to really engage.

00:17:17.653 --> 00:17:18.527
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Yeah.

00:17:18.527 --> 00:17:19.902
So I mean, speed
dating is great.

00:17:19.902 --> 00:17:22.568
You meet a whole bunch of people
in a very short amount of time,

00:17:22.568 --> 00:17:24.260
but what if you meet
that person and you

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:25.020
got a little bit of a spark?

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:27.039
You want to get to
know them a little bit.

00:17:27.039 --> 00:17:29.580
ELISABETH MORANT: Exactly, and
native apps are great at this.

00:17:29.580 --> 00:17:29.830
ALEX KOMOROSKE: OK.

00:17:29.830 --> 00:17:30.690
I've got an idea.

00:17:30.690 --> 00:17:32.231
Why don't we just
list all the things

00:17:32.231 --> 00:17:34.439
native apps can do and
just copy that for the web?

00:17:34.439 --> 00:17:36.480
ELISABETH MORANT: Well,
I wish it were that easy.

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:38.640
The problem is that
with every new API also

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:41.260
comes a whole new
set of risks, and we

00:17:41.260 --> 00:17:42.980
want to maintain the
security guarantees

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:45.390
of the web, the ability
for users to jump to a link

00:17:45.390 --> 00:17:47.820
and not worry that something's
going to happen to them.

00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:50.560
So let's take, for example,
background sync, background

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:56.050
sync being the ability for an
app to fetch and send content

00:17:56.050 --> 00:17:58.300
when the app is closed.

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:01.759
So if you're visiting
over 100 sites a month,

00:18:01.759 --> 00:18:04.300
then you don't necessarily want
them all to arbitrarily start

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:05.840
syncing the background.

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:08.700
Just like let's say you
browse some embarrassing sites

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:10.630
at home, like some
celebrity gossip site.

00:18:10.630 --> 00:18:12.577
I'm not going to call
what celebrity Alex is

00:18:12.577 --> 00:18:13.160
obsessed with.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:13.760
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Guilty.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:15.150
ELISABETH MORANT: And
then you go to work,

00:18:15.150 --> 00:18:16.900
and in the meantime,
your phone lost battery.

00:18:16.900 --> 00:18:18.520
You turn it on when you get
to work, and all of a sudden,

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:20.686
you start fetching embarrassing
content while you're

00:18:20.686 --> 00:18:22.009
on your corporate network.

00:18:22.009 --> 00:18:23.800
Well, we're trying to
save people like Alex

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:26.099
from an embarrassing visit
to the sys admin's office.

00:18:26.099 --> 00:18:26.890
ALEX KOMOROSKE: OK.

00:18:26.890 --> 00:18:27.900
I get that.

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:28.890
I see.

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:31.056
ELISABETH MORANT: And so
basically, if we bring back

00:18:31.056 --> 00:18:33.020
the speed dating
metaphor, let's say

00:18:33.020 --> 00:18:35.380
that you meet someone
for the first time

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:37.660
and you really feel that
spark and you think,

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:39.030
this could be the one.

00:18:39.030 --> 00:18:40.902
Do you give them the
keys to your apartment,

00:18:40.902 --> 00:18:43.110
introduce them to your
parents, bend down on one knee

00:18:43.110 --> 00:18:44.790
and vow to spend the rest
of your life together?

00:18:44.790 --> 00:18:45.230
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Yes.

00:18:45.230 --> 00:18:46.105
ELISABETH MORANT: No.

00:18:46.105 --> 00:18:47.670
Of course not.

00:18:47.670 --> 00:18:50.750
Jeez, that could
be a serial killer.

00:18:50.750 --> 00:18:54.580
So the idea is that you want
to build a relationship slowly.

00:18:54.580 --> 00:18:58.110
The problem is that we can't
necessarily emulate or copy

00:18:58.110 --> 00:18:59.780
the powerful model
of native apps

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:02.840
because native apps have a
store, they have ops teams,

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:04.360
and the web is open.

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:06.720
And so what we want
to do is enable

00:19:06.720 --> 00:19:09.130
websites to progressively
ask permission

00:19:09.130 --> 00:19:11.270
for powerful and
engaging features.

00:19:11.270 --> 00:19:12.810
And the idea is
that users should

00:19:12.810 --> 00:19:14.710
be able to indicate
when they want

00:19:14.710 --> 00:19:18.390
to trust this site enough to
give them certain permissions.

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:21.240
Basically, if everyone got
access to your bank account

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:23.030
as soon as you met
them, you probably

00:19:23.030 --> 00:19:24.480
wouldn't want to
leave your house.

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:26.520
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So it's
more important for the reach

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:28.480
of the web than to have
all these capabilities

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:29.860
for every random site you go to.

00:19:29.860 --> 00:19:30.250
ELISABETH MORANT: Exactly.

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:31.420
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Got it.

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:32.795
ELISABETH MORANT:
And so the idea

00:19:32.795 --> 00:19:35.230
is that with all these new
APIs come a set of risks,

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:37.380
and Chrome has
this responsibility

00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:41.089
to make sure that people can
still browse the web securely.

00:19:41.089 --> 00:19:42.630
Now, with this in
mind, we've already

00:19:42.630 --> 00:19:44.600
brought a few exciting
APIs to the web

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:47.530
and we're going to talk
about two of them right now.

00:19:47.530 --> 00:19:49.800
The first is Add to Homescreen.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:52.440
So typing, especially
on a mobile,

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:55.482
is really hard, but mobile is
where people go to kill time.

00:19:55.482 --> 00:19:57.690
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So, I mean,
you go to the coffee shop

00:19:57.690 --> 00:19:58.523
to meet your friend.

00:19:58.523 --> 00:19:59.564
They aren't there yet.

00:19:59.564 --> 00:20:01.480
You want to read something
interesting but not

00:20:01.480 --> 00:20:03.830
too interesting because at
any point they might show up

00:20:03.830 --> 00:20:04.850
and you have to put
your phone away.

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:05.933
ELISABETH MORANT: Exactly.

00:20:05.933 --> 00:20:08.190
So you open up your
phone, you tap an icon,

00:20:08.190 --> 00:20:10.700
and you fall into
some experience

00:20:10.700 --> 00:20:14.690
that you're OK jumping
back out of again.

00:20:14.690 --> 00:20:17.210
And so we already have
the ability for people

00:20:17.210 --> 00:20:18.890
to add sites to
their home screen.

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:20.800
It's buried deep
in the settings,

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:22.634
but we found it had
surprisingly high usage.

00:20:22.634 --> 00:20:25.258
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So why don't we
just make that way more obvious

00:20:25.258 --> 00:20:26.592
and make it really hard to miss?

00:20:26.592 --> 00:20:27.966
ELISABETH MORANT:
Well, if people

00:20:27.966 --> 00:20:29.550
are visiting 100
websites every month,

00:20:29.550 --> 00:20:33.300
then probably every new
help form you go to,

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:35.860
you don't want to necessarily
add it to your home screen.

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:38.700
And so what we've done is we've
incorporated some really smart

00:20:38.700 --> 00:20:41.490
heuristics and said
developers can use this API

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:43.520
and request to be added
to the home screen

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:46.190
as long as people have in
each with the app enough

00:20:46.190 --> 00:20:48.410
that we've detected
that they actually want

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:50.890
that app on their home screen.

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:53.170
So take this as an example.

00:20:53.170 --> 00:20:55.920
I really enjoy
reading Vice News,

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:58.050
and I read an article
earlier this week.

00:20:58.050 --> 00:21:00.060
And this morning I
opened it up again,

00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:02.990
And I found that I got this
prompt from Vice to add

00:21:02.990 --> 00:21:05.749
the website to my home screen.

00:21:05.749 --> 00:21:06.540
ALEX KOMOROSKE: OK.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:08.539
That's awesome, but what
happens if you tap that

00:21:08.539 --> 00:21:09.950
and you don't have connectivity?

00:21:09.950 --> 00:21:10.680
ELISABETH MORANT:
Well, what you don't

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:13.210
want to see is the
dreaded offline dinosaur,

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:16.020
and so native apps actually
handle this case very well.

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:18.790
Even if an app depends
on connectivity to work,

00:21:18.790 --> 00:21:21.230
they usually have some sort
of splash screen saying,

00:21:21.230 --> 00:21:23.420
sorry, you can't use
this, but come back later,

00:21:23.420 --> 00:21:24.826
something custom to the app.

00:21:24.826 --> 00:21:26.450
And for that reason,
we've only enabled

00:21:26.450 --> 00:21:28.040
Add to Homescreen
for those sites that

00:21:28.040 --> 00:21:29.840
have a meaningful
offline experience.

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:30.760
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Which
is a great point

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:32.830
that offline is an
incredibly important thing

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:35.910
for building engaging
experiences on mobile web.

00:21:35.910 --> 00:21:38.240
So obviously, on
your mobile devices,

00:21:38.240 --> 00:21:42.100
you're way more likely to
have a flaky connectivity

00:21:42.100 --> 00:21:45.190
or no connectivity, like being
at a tech conference where

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:47.700
the Wi-Fi doesn't work
exactly as it should.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:49.740
The problem is that
historically, we've only

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.150
had App Cache to handle this.

00:21:51.150 --> 00:21:53.630
ELISABETH MORANT: So what's
the problem with App Cache?

00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:56.900
ALEX KOMOROSKE: App Cache
wasn't exactly very popular.

00:21:56.900 --> 00:22:00.070
So it was easy to get
started, which is great,

00:22:00.070 --> 00:22:02.480
and it's declarative,
which is also great,

00:22:02.480 --> 00:22:04.190
but it's kind of complex.

00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:06.822
If you do anything
rather slightly complex,

00:22:06.822 --> 00:22:08.405
you can't do the
things you want to do

00:22:08.405 --> 00:22:09.712
and it quickly falls down.

00:22:09.712 --> 00:22:10.920
It is unworkable in practice.

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:13.670
So what you need, of
course, is more control,

00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:16.180
and Service Worker
brings you that control.

00:22:16.180 --> 00:22:18.620
So let me tell you how it works.

00:22:18.620 --> 00:22:21.320
The basic idea is
when you visit a site,

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:22.941
you can install
a Service Worker,

00:22:22.941 --> 00:22:24.440
and that Service
Worker is basically

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:26.670
a script off to the side.

00:22:26.670 --> 00:22:29.700
And now, when the
browser is going

00:22:29.700 --> 00:22:32.260
to fetch a resource
from your domain,

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:34.200
instead of going
to the network, it

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:36.740
asks the Service Worker,
hey, what do you want to do?

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:38.454
And the Service Worker
can say, just do

00:22:38.454 --> 00:22:40.620
what you would have done,
go to the network, please,

00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:44.260
or it can say, please hand
back this thing from the cache,

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:47.900
or it can even say, create
a resource on the fly

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:48.500
and pass that.

00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:50.000
ELISABETH MORANT:
So basically, it's

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.001
a client side proxy
written in JavaScript.

00:22:52.001 --> 00:22:53.000
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Exactly.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.890
So this allows you
to build arbitrarily

00:22:55.890 --> 00:22:57.970
complex offline experiences.

00:22:57.970 --> 00:23:00.000
And when I say "arbitrarily,"
what I mean is you

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.780
can build something extremely
complex or extremely simple.

00:23:03.780 --> 00:23:05.920
So the I/O web app
is a great example

00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:07.730
of a complex offline web app.

00:23:07.730 --> 00:23:10.727
It does very careful caching
so that even if you load it

00:23:10.727 --> 00:23:13.060
when you're fully offline,
you get something meaningful,

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:15.700
but then when you're connected,
it will show you UI about, hey,

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:16.616
there's fresh content.

00:23:16.616 --> 00:23:18.530
Tap here to see it.

00:23:18.530 --> 00:23:21.090
Of course, a more likely
scenario or easier scenario

00:23:21.090 --> 00:23:23.580
is just to aggressively
cache everything

00:23:23.580 --> 00:23:26.340
you use so that your
thing works offline.

00:23:26.340 --> 00:23:29.520
There's a great Gulp
plug-in called sw-precache

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:32.950
that makes it incredibly easy to
integrate into your workflows.

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:35.460
And of course, the simplest
possible thing you can do

00:23:35.460 --> 00:23:38.400
is get rid of that darn
offline dinosaur for your thing

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:41.720
and basically say,
hey Service Worker,

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:45.520
if the user tries to fetch my
site and we're fully offline,

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:47.250
instead of showing
the offline dinosaur,

00:23:47.250 --> 00:23:49.010
just show my own
little splash screen

00:23:49.010 --> 00:23:52.200
that says, please connect to
the internet and try again.

00:23:52.200 --> 00:23:55.630
That takes only a few
lines of JavaScript.

00:23:55.630 --> 00:23:57.900
So Service Worker
is cool for offline,

00:23:57.900 --> 00:23:59.690
but it has another
trick up its sleeve.

00:23:59.690 --> 00:24:03.780
So a Service Worker, a single
one, can talk to multiple tabs

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:06.540
or it can talk to no tabs.

00:24:06.540 --> 00:24:09.800
So it's the first place that
we as developers have a place

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:13.240
to write and run script even
when no tabs for my site

00:24:13.240 --> 00:24:13.970
are open.

00:24:13.970 --> 00:24:15.178
ELISABETH MORANT: That's bad.

00:24:15.178 --> 00:24:17.127
People don't want any
random site executing

00:24:17.127 --> 00:24:18.210
scripts in the background.

00:24:18.210 --> 00:24:19.160
ALEX KOMOROSKE:
Exactly, and that's

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:21.190
why Service Workers
are event driven.

00:24:21.190 --> 00:24:23.841
So what happens is a networking
event happens, the browser goes

00:24:23.841 --> 00:24:25.340
to the Service
Worker and says, hey,

00:24:25.340 --> 00:24:26.830
I've got this network event.

00:24:26.830 --> 00:24:28.706
Service worker handles
it and then it's done.

00:24:28.706 --> 00:24:30.913
It's just sitting there not
doing anything because it

00:24:30.913 --> 00:24:31.525
can't.

00:24:31.525 --> 00:24:33.650
And so at that point, we
can freeze dry that thing,

00:24:33.650 --> 00:24:34.880
put it off in storage.

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:36.370
ELISABETH MORANT: Right, until
the browser sends a new event

00:24:36.370 --> 00:24:37.140
to wake it up.

00:24:37.140 --> 00:24:37.600
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Exactly.

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.330
So when a new event
comes in, we bring it

00:24:39.330 --> 00:24:41.205
back into memory really
quickly, which takes,

00:24:41.205 --> 00:24:44.580
I think, around 50 milliseconds
or so in practice in the wild,

00:24:44.580 --> 00:24:47.070
and then it can go on its way.

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:49.630
So the cool thing is that
this isn't just related

00:24:49.630 --> 00:24:52.180
to network events.

00:24:52.180 --> 00:24:54.620
You can also imagine
other types of events

00:24:54.620 --> 00:24:57.110
that would potentially
wake it up to do work.

00:24:57.110 --> 00:24:57.340
ELISABETH MORANT: I see.

00:24:57.340 --> 00:24:58.975
So the browser can
choose what type of event

00:24:58.975 --> 00:25:01.450
it wants to send based on what
it thinks the user actually

00:25:01.450 --> 00:25:01.950
wants.

00:25:01.950 --> 00:25:02.950
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Exactly.

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:04.340
So this is really powerful.

00:25:04.340 --> 00:25:06.960
It enables an entirely
new class of functionality

00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:10.590
that before wasn't even
possible to bring to the web.

00:25:10.590 --> 00:25:12.840
ELISABETH MORANT: So one of
the new features only made

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:16.430
possible because of Service
Worker is push notifications.

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:18.465
Until now, only native
apps were able to send

00:25:18.465 --> 00:25:19.840
push notifications,
but there are

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:22.850
cases where you would want push
without everything else that

00:25:22.850 --> 00:25:24.285
comes with being an app.

00:25:24.285 --> 00:25:25.910
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So
are these important?

00:25:25.910 --> 00:25:26.140
ELISABETH MORANT: Yeah.

00:25:26.140 --> 00:25:27.900
This is extremely important.

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:31.240
Basically, notifications are
game changing for engagement.

00:25:31.240 --> 00:25:33.550
More and more, people are
interacting with their phone,

00:25:33.550 --> 00:25:36.090
opening up new apps
and experiences largely

00:25:36.090 --> 00:25:37.970
because they got a
notification first,

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:40.780
and it's much less common that
people will open up their phone

00:25:40.780 --> 00:25:42.242
and dumbly look
at their app grid

00:25:42.242 --> 00:25:44.380
and decide what
they want to use.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:45.440
Here's an example.

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:47.930
So the Guardian has
a native app and they

00:25:47.930 --> 00:25:52.890
found that in the hours after a
breaking news event, up to 40%

00:25:52.890 --> 00:25:55.930
of their article views came
from push notifications alone.

00:25:55.930 --> 00:25:57.005
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Wow.

00:25:57.005 --> 00:25:58.330
ELISABETH MORANT: It's huge.

00:25:58.330 --> 00:26:00.360
And so to demonstrate
how important this is,

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:02.560
I'm going to jump into a demo.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:07.674
So nine months ago, Oscars
season, I was at home

00:26:07.674 --> 00:26:09.090
but I had to do a
lot of work so I

00:26:09.090 --> 00:26:11.470
wasn't able to watch
the Academy Awards live.

00:26:11.470 --> 00:26:14.170
This was a huge bummer for me,
so what I ended up doing was

00:26:14.170 --> 00:26:17.100
I would jump between
my computer and then I

00:26:17.100 --> 00:26:20.720
kept refreshing the Guardian
live blog to see who had won.

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:22.350
And what I would
do is I'd refresh

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.990
and I'd see what Reese
Witherspoon is wearing,

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:26.640
and then I'd click
on that and look

00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:28.830
at some of her past filmography,
and then just get distracted

00:26:28.830 --> 00:26:30.180
and jump back to my computer.

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:31.380
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Basically,
getting nothing done.

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:32.338
ELISABETH MORANT: Yeah.

00:26:32.338 --> 00:26:34.828
Basically, I was not getting
anything done, or at least

00:26:34.828 --> 00:26:37.360
I wasn't getting a
lot of work done.

00:26:37.360 --> 00:26:41.090
But what if the Guardian
had push notifications?

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:43.600
What if I didn't have
to jump in and engage

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:46.070
and instead the Guardian told
me when there was information

00:26:46.070 --> 00:26:48.080
that I actually wanted to know.

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:53.520
So suppose I open up the
live blog and I scroll down

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:56.130
and I see the ability
to follow the story.

00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:58.152
So the Guardian
explains why I'd want

00:26:58.152 --> 00:26:59.690
to opt in to
notifications, I want

00:26:59.690 --> 00:27:01.930
to engage with this
particular piece of content,

00:27:01.930 --> 00:27:05.064
so I hit Enable
Browser Notifications.

00:27:05.064 --> 00:27:06.980
And at this point, Chrome
sends me the prompt,

00:27:06.980 --> 00:27:11.020
and yes, I want
notifications, so I say Allow.

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:11.710
Great.

00:27:11.710 --> 00:27:14.050
So, now confident that I'm
going to get notifications

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:15.549
about the content
I'm interested in,

00:27:15.549 --> 00:27:22.110
I can just close Chrome
and get back to work.

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:29.420
So I'm working and I
see a notification.

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:30.760
I don't know if you can see it.

00:27:30.760 --> 00:27:32.740
I haven't tested this out.

00:27:32.740 --> 00:27:34.670
So I see a notification
on my watch

00:27:34.670 --> 00:27:37.780
that says that sound
editing won some award.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:41.170
Now, this is one of those lame
awards so I just swipe it away.

00:27:41.170 --> 00:27:42.160
I don't care.

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:43.150
ALEX KOMOROSKE: So you
got that on your watch?

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:44.108
ELISABETH MORANT: Yeah.

00:27:44.108 --> 00:27:46.990
I got it on my watch because
Chrome sends notifications

00:27:46.990 --> 00:27:49.719
just like any other Android app
would, and in that same way,

00:27:49.719 --> 00:27:51.510
I get notifications on
my phone just like I

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:53.840
do from my messaging apps.

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:58.090
So I wasn't interested in that
content, so I go back to work,

00:27:58.090 --> 00:28:03.375
drinking coffee, eating donuts,
writing very important briefs.

00:28:06.391 --> 00:28:06.890
Oh.

00:28:06.890 --> 00:28:08.470
I see another notification.

00:28:08.470 --> 00:28:13.190
And this one, of course,
"Birdman" won best picture.

00:28:13.190 --> 00:28:15.689
I mean, clearly we all know
that the movie that should have

00:28:15.689 --> 00:28:16.980
won the award was "The Grand--"

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:19.520
ALEX KOMOROSKE: Wait, wait.

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:22.040
ELISABETH MORANT: "The
Grand Budapest Hotel,"

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:25.690
which I'm sure everyone else in
the room agrees with me about.

00:28:25.690 --> 00:28:27.430
So in order to
express my opinion,

00:28:27.430 --> 00:28:31.690
maybe I'll dive into the live
blog, open up the website,

00:28:31.690 --> 00:28:34.830
maybe leave a few very
tastefully written comments

00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:37.490
about why this movie
