00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:54.010
At Google I/O two
or three years ago,

00:34:54.010 --> 00:34:57.086
they were using offline
storage for Angry Birds.

00:34:57.086 --> 00:34:58.960
What's the advantage of
using Service Worker?

00:34:58.960 --> 00:35:00.335
ALEX KOMOROSKE:
So Service Worker

00:35:00.335 --> 00:35:03.094
allows you to have very
fine grained control

00:35:03.094 --> 00:35:05.260
over all aspects of what's
happening on the network,

00:35:05.260 --> 00:35:10.020
so then you can use technologies
like Index DB and Explicit

00:35:10.020 --> 00:35:12.690
Cache API to do stuff,
whereas before, you

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:15.450
were limited to a very high
level declarative approach.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:17.842
If it worked for you, it
was great, but more likely

00:35:17.842 --> 00:35:18.800
it didn't work for you.

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:20.520
It couldn't do exactly
what you wanted

00:35:20.520 --> 00:35:22.330
to handle in this
particular case

00:35:22.330 --> 00:35:23.790
and so it was basically useless.

00:35:23.790 --> 00:35:25.680
So Service Worker,
the way to think of it

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:29.260
is-- are you familiar with
the Extensible Web Manifesto?

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:30.740
So that's a notion
that we should

00:35:30.740 --> 00:35:32.640
be defining the lower
level primitives that

00:35:32.640 --> 00:35:34.657
explain how the
web platform works,

00:35:34.657 --> 00:35:36.240
so getting rid of
the high level magic

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:39.470
and giving developers access to
the low level primitives that

00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:41.030
make that magic work.

00:35:41.030 --> 00:35:42.830
So Service Worker
is like digging

00:35:42.830 --> 00:35:46.190
down deep below App Cache
to figure out what was there

00:35:46.190 --> 00:35:48.190
and how it worked and
expose that to developers.

00:35:48.190 --> 00:35:49.380
Does that make sense?

00:35:49.380 --> 00:35:51.068
Probably not, but OK.

